Japan, South Korea, Thailand, Philippines: Asia Bonds and Currency Preview

-- B y   A n i l   V a r m a
-- 
2011-05-23T23:14:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-23/japan-south-korea-thailand-philippines-asia-bonds-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan : Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Edano will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in  Tokyo . The Bank of Japan will release its
monthly economic report for May at 2:00 p.m.  The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond maturing in
March 2021 was at 1.12 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading
Co. The yen traded at 81.97 as of 7:51 a.m. in Tokyo.  South Korea: The central bank will report on the nation’s
short-term external debt for the first quarter. The amount was
$135 billion for the three months ended Dec. 31.  The yield on  South Korea ’s 3 percent bond due December 2013
was 3.59 percent. The won was at 1,097.80 per dollar.  China : The central bank plans to sell 3 billion yuan ($461
million) of one-year notes.  The yield on the 3.83 percent bond due March 2021 was 3.84
percent, according to Chinabond, the nation’s biggest debt-
clearing house. The yuan was at 6.5050.  Indonesia: The government plans to sell one-year bills and
five- and 10-year bonds.  The yield on the 8.25 percent bond due July 2021 was 7.43
percent. The rupiah was at 8,588.  Thailand: The central bank will auction 25 billion baht
($822 million) of 28-day bills, 22 billion baht of 91-day notes
and 15 billion baht of 182-day securities.  The yield on the 3.125 percent debt due December 2015 was
3.45 percent. The baht was at 30.40 per dollar.  Philippines : The government will offer 9 billion pesos
($208 million) of four-year debt securities.  The yield on the 6.50 percent bond due April 2021 was 6.49
percent, according to Tradition Financial Services. The peso was
at 43.41 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Anil Varma in Mumbai at 
